ᱢᱤᱱᱟᱠᱥᱤ ᱪᱤᱛᱚᱨᱚᱧᱡᱚᱱ ᱫᱚ ᱵᱷᱟᱨᱚᱛ ᱫᱤᱥᱚᱢ ᱨᱤᱱᱤᱡ ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢᱟᱱ ᱠᱞᱟᱥᱤᱠᱟᱞ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱨᱩᱥᱤᱠᱟ ᱠᱟᱱᱟᱭ ᱾ ᱵᱷᱟᱨᱚᱛᱱᱟᱴᱭᱚᱢ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱦᱟᱹᱴᱤᱧ ᱨᱮᱱᱟᱜ ᱯᱟᱱᱰᱟᱞᱩᱨ ᱞᱮᱠᱟᱱ ᱠᱞᱟᱥᱤᱠᱟᱞ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱨᱤᱱᱤᱡ ᱢᱤᱫ ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢᱟᱱ ᱢᱟᱪᱮᱛ ᱟᱨ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱰᱟᱦᱟᱨ ᱩᱱᱩᱫᱩᱜ ᱤᱡ ᱠᱟᱱᱟᱭ ᱾ <ref name="Profile: Meenakshi Chitharanjan">{{cite web | url=http://www.lokvani.com/lokvani/article.php?article_id=5567 | title=Profile: Meenakshi Chitharanjan | publisher=Lokvani | date=17 March 2009 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> She is the founder of ''Kaladiksha'', an institution promoting Bharatanatyam and striving to preserve the [[Pandanallur style|Pandanallur tradition]]. A disciple of the father-son duo of Chokkalingam Pillai and Subbaraya Pillai,<ref name="The king was captivated and…">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-king-was-captivated-and/article6549572.ece | title=The king was captivated and… | publisher=The Hindu | date=31 October 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>

ᱵᱷᱟᱨᱚᱛᱱᱟᱴᱭᱚᱢ ᱟᱨ ᱚᱱᱟ ᱨᱮᱱᱟᱜ ᱦᱟᱹᱴᱤᱧ ᱯᱟᱱᱰᱟᱞᱩᱨ ᱞᱮᱠᱟᱱ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱠᱚ ᱵᱟᱧᱪᱟᱣ ᱟᱨ ᱦᱟᱨᱟ ᱵᱩᱨᱩ ᱞᱟᱹᱜᱤᱫ ᱠᱟᱞᱟᱫᱤᱠᱥᱟ ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢ ᱜᱟᱶᱛᱟ ᱟᱡ ᱮ ᱵᱮᱱᱟᱣ ᱠᱮᱜᱼᱟ ᱾ ᱪᱳᱠᱠᱟᱞᱤᱸᱜᱚᱢ ᱯᱤᱞᱟᱤ ᱟᱨ ᱥᱩᱵᱵᱚᱨᱟᱭᱟ ᱯᱤᱞᱟᱤ, ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢ ᱢᱤᱫ ᱟᱯᱟᱦᱚᱯᱚᱱ ᱟᱡ ᱨᱤᱱ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱜᱩᱨᱩ ᱠᱤᱱ ᱛᱟᱦᱮᱸ ᱠᱟᱱᱟ ᱾ <ref name="The king was captivated and…">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-king-was-captivated-and/article6549572.ece | title=The king was captivated and… | publisher=The Hindu | date=31 October 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>
she is a recipient of several honours including [[Kalaimamani]] Award of the Government of Tamil Nadu and the ''Natya Kala Sarathi'' of ''Sri Parthasarathy Swami Sabha''.<ref name="Life’s dancing lessons">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/lifes-dancing-lessons/article5684655.ece | title=Life’s dancing lessons | publisher=The Hindu | date=13 February 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  
ᱱᱩᱭ ᱫᱚ ᱟᱭᱢᱟ ᱞᱮᱠᱟᱱ ᱥᱟᱨᱦᱟᱣ ᱮ ᱧᱟᱢ ᱟᱠᱟᱫᱼᱟ ᱾ ᱚᱱᱟᱠᱚ ᱢᱩᱫᱽᱨᱮ ᱛᱟᱢᱤᱞᱱᱟᱰᱩ ᱥᱟᱨᱠᱟᱨᱤ ᱯᱟᱦᱴᱟ ᱠᱷᱚᱱ ᱠᱟᱞᱟᱭᱤᱢᱟᱢᱚᱱᱤ ᱟᱨ ᱯᱟᱨᱛᱷᱚᱥᱟᱨᱚᱛᱷᱤ ᱥᱣᱟᱢᱤ ᱥᱚᱵᱷᱟ ᱯᱟᱦᱴᱟ ᱠᱷᱚᱱ ᱱᱟᱴᱭᱚ ᱠᱟᱞᱟ ᱥᱟᱨᱚᱛᱷᱤ ᱥᱟᱨᱦᱟᱣ ᱮ ᱧᱟᱢ ᱟᱠᱟᱫᱼᱟ ᱾ publisher=The Hindu | date=31 October 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> she is a recipient of several honours including [[Kalaimamani]] Award of the Government of Tamil Nadu and the ''Natya Kala Sarathi'' of ''Sri Parthasarathy Swami Sabha''.<ref name="Life’s dancing lessons">{{cite web | url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/dance/lifes-dancing-lessons/article5684655.ece | title=Life’s dancing lessons | ᱵᱷᱟᱨᱟᱛᱱᱟᱴᱭᱟᱢ ᱠᱞᱟᱥᱤᱠᱟᱞ ᱮᱱᱮᱡ ᱨᱮ ᱟᱡ ᱱᱟᱯᱟᱭ ᱮᱱᱮᱢ ᱠᱷᱟᱹᱛᱤᱨ ᱵᱷᱟᱨᱚᱛ ᱥᱟᱨᱠᱟᱨ ᱯᱟᱦᱴᱟ ᱠᱷᱚᱱ ᱦᱚᱸ ᱥᱟᱞ ᱒᱐᱐᱘ ᱨᱮ ᱯᱩᱱᱟᱜ ᱧᱩᱛᱩᱢᱟᱱ ᱥᱟᱨᱦᱟᱣ ᱥᱚᱢᱢᱟᱱ ᱯᱚᱫᱢᱚᱥᱨᱤ ᱥᱚᱢᱢᱟᱱ ᱛᱮᱠᱚ ᱥᱟᱨᱦᱟᱣ ᱟᱠᱟ ᱫᱮᱭᱟ ᱾ publisher=The Hindu | date=13 February 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> The Government of India awarded her the fourth highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Shri]], in 2008, for her contributions to classical dance.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2016 |accessdate=3 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 }}</ref>
